2. Removing 50 Hz noise¶

In this notebook, we'll show how we removed the power line interference, using a function composed of one or multiple sine waves around 50 Hz.

In [4]:
def sin_1(t, A, w, p):
    return A * np.sin(w*t + p)

def sin_2(t, A1, w1, p1, A2, w2, p2):
    return A1 * np.sin(w1*t + p1) + A2 * np.sin(w2*t + p2)

def get_guess(tt, yy):
    ff = np.fft.fftfreq(len(tt), (tt[1]-tt[0]))   # assume uniform spacing
    Fyy = abs(np.fft.fft(yy))
    return [0., 2.*np.pi*abs(ff[np.argmax(Fyy[1:])+1]), 0.]

def fit_sin1(tt, yy):
    '''Fit sine wave to the input time sequence'''
    # Taken from: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/16716302/how-do-i-fit-a-sine-curve-to-my-data-with-pylab-and-numpy
    guess = np.array(get_guess(tt, yy))
    popt, pcov = opt.curve_fit(sin_1, tt, yy, p0=guess, maxfev=10000)
    return {"parameters": popt, "fitfunc": lambda t: sin_1(t, *popt)}

def fit_sin2(tt, yy):
    '''Fit sum of 2 sine waves to the input time sequence'''
    # Taken from: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/16716302/how-do-i-fit-a-sine-curve-to-my-data-with-pylab-and-numpy
    guess = np.array(get_guess(tt, yy) * 2)
    popt, pcov = opt.curve_fit(sin_2, tt, yy, p0=guess, maxfev=10000)
    return {"parameters": popt, "fitfunc": lambda t: sin_2(t, *popt)}

def remove_sine(signal, channels, c):
    # This noise calculation worked better than a simple signal - channels
    noise = signal - (0.2 * channels + 0.8 * np.round(channels))
    noise = np.clip(noise, -0.8, 0.8)
    noise = noise - np.median(noise)
    
    if c != 5:
        results = fit_sin1(np.arange(len(noise)), noise)
    else:
        results = fit_sin2(np.arange(len(noise)), noise)
    
    plt.figure()
    plt.plot(noise[:10000])
    plt.plot(results['fitfunc'](np.arange(len(signal)))[:10000])
    plt.show()
    
    if c == 5:
        print(results['parameters'])
    
    return signal - results['fitfunc'](np.arange(len(signal)))

signal = np.concatenate((train['signal'].values, test['signal'].values))
for i, (start, end) in enumerate(zip(BATCHES[:-1], BATCHES[1:])):
    c = CATEGORIES[i]
    for k in range(end - start):
        sub_start = (start + k) * 100_000
        sub_end = (start + k + 1) * 100_000
        signal[sub_start:sub_end] = remove_sine(signal[sub_start:sub_end], 
                                                predictions[sub_start:sub_end], c)
train['signal'] = signal[:5_000_000]
test['signal'] = signal[5_000_000:]
